    <strong style="font-weight:bold;font-size:16px;color:rgb(0, 0, 0);padding-right:6px;">Roy</strong>
    
    
    <span style="font-size:15px;display:inline-block;padding:0px 10px 0px 2px;padding-left:0px;background-image:none;background-attachment:initial;background-color:initial;background-origin:initial;background-clip:initial;background-repeat:initial;">ex-Whole Foods</span>
    

  </div>
  
														<p style="margin:0px 0px 30px;font-size:16px;line-height:23px;font-weight:300;font-family:nyt-franklin, arial, sans-serif;padding:0px;width:auto;color:rgb(34, 34, 34);display:inline-block;">I was an hourly-paid supervisor at Whole Foods for 3 1/2 years. With rare exceptions, everyone's schedule changed each week. We were told the company was not obligated to produce schedules beyond four days in advance and were frequently given just two days notice. Scheduling requests (a day off here, a late shift there, but nothing regular) were usually honored, provided they were submitted two weeks in advance. Clopening was permitted if you had eight hours between shifts. I never took pharmaceuticals, but had to rely on sleeping pills to cope. "Team member happiness" was an official core value.</p>
  
