													</li>


													<li style="font-size:1rem;line-height:1.4375rem;font-weight:400;font-family:georgia, 'times new roman', times, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;cursor:auto;background-image:none;background-attachment:initial;background-color:initial;background-origin:initial;background-clip:initial;background-repeat:initial;">
  
														<div style="margin:0px 0px 2px;font-family:nyt-franklin, arial, helvetica, sans-serif;color:rgb(102, 102, 102);font-size:12px;">
    
    
    <strong style="font-weight:bold;font-size:16px;color:rgb(0, 0, 0);padding-right:6px;">Lindsey Reichlin</strong>
    
    <span style="font-size:15px;display:inline-block;padding:0px 10px 0px 2px;padding-left:0px;">Washington, DC</span>
    <span style="font-size:15px;display:inline-block;padding:0px 10px 0px 2px;background-image:none;background-attachment:initial;background-color:initial;background-origin:initial;background-clip:initial;background-repeat:initial;">Institute for Women's Policy Research </span>
    

  </div>
  
														<p style="margin:0px 0px 30px;font-size:16px;line-height:23px;font-weight:300;font-family:nyt-franklin, arial, sans-serif;padding:0px;width:auto;color:rgb(34, 34, 34);display:inline-block;">The struggles faced by Ms. Navarro are representative of those endured by millions of college students around the United States, more than a quarter of which are juggling school and parenthood. While work is often critical to a student’s ability to pursue a college education, especially when that student is raising a dependent child, unpredictable and inflexible work schedules pose a significant challenge to their ultimate success, both in attaining a degree and in the labor market. Policies that improve employer scheduling practices would improve chances of success among women, especially single moms, pursuing postsecondary degrees. www.iwpr.org/publications/pubs/community-college-students-need-fair-job-scheduling-practices.</p>
  
														<div style="opacity:0;height:22px;padding-bottom:25px;display:none !important;"><span style="display:inline-block;margin-right:8px;margin-bottom:-2px;"><a style="text-decoration:none;color:rgb(50, 104, 145);" href="http://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/08/13/us/starbucks-workers-scheduling-hours.html?_r=2#"><i style="display:inline-block;line-height:0;vertical-align:middle;font-style:normal;width:12px;height:12px;margin:-4px 0px 0px;background-image:url(&amp;apos;http://graphics8.nytimes.com/newsgraphics/2014/07/23/workers/e74e3e5cd5123f61561477df663fabfdcb7f0212/url(http://a1.nyt.com/assets/article/20140720-215816/images/sprite/sprite-no-repeat.png)');background-attachment:initial;background-color:initial;background-origin:initial;background-clip:initial;background-position:0px -20px;background-repeat:no-repeat;"></i></a><span style="position:absolute;width:1px;height:1px;margin:-1px;padding:0px;border:0px;clip:rect(0px 0px 0px 0px);overflow:hidden;display:inline-block;margin-right:8px;margin-bottom:-2px;">Share this comment on Facebook</span></span><span style="display:inline-block;margin-right:8px;margin-bottom:-2px;"><a style="text-decoration:none;color:rgb(50, 104, 145);" href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=http://localhost.nytimes.com:8000&amp;text=Comment%20On:%20Working%20Anything%20but%209%20to%205&amp;via=nytimes"><i style="display:inline-block;line-height:0;vertical-align:middle;font-style:normal;width:12px;height:12px;margin-top:-4px;background-image:url(&amp;apos;http://graphics8.nytimes.com/newsgraphics/2014/07/23/workers/e74e3e5cd5123f61561477df663fabfdcb7f0212/url(http://a1.nyt.com/assets/article/20140720-215816/images/sprite/sprite-no-repeat.png)');background-attachment:initial;background-color:initial;background-origin:initial;background-clip:initial;background-position:-12px -145px;background-repeat:no-repeat;"></i></a><span style="position:absolute;width:1px;height:1px;margin:-1px;padding:0px;border:0px;clip:rect(0px 0px 0p